<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-position-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Position Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                <p>Determine translation vector as a transformation</p>
            </li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Grade Level</title>
                <p>Grade 10</p>
            </li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                <p>40 minutes</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>By the end of this lesson, learners should be able to:</alert>
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Know:</alert> The definition of a position vector as a vector from the origin to a specific point in the plane.
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Do:</alert> Determine position vectors of given points; distinguish between position vectors and displacement vectors.
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Apply:</alert> Use position vectors to describe locations relative to a reference point in navigation and GPS contexts.
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/position-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_position-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organize students into groups of 2–3.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Materials:</alert> Graph paper, rulers, pencils, coloured markers.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Circulate among students, ensuring they plot points correctly.</li>
                <li>Ask probing questions: <q>Where is the origin? What is the position of point A?</q></li>
                <li>For struggling students: <q>Let us draw the line from O to A together. What are the coordinates of A?</q></li>
                <li>For early finishers: <q>Can you find the position vectors of points C and D?</q></li>
                <li>Guide students to articulate: a position vector starts from the origin and points to a specific location.</li>
                <li>Identify 2–3 students with clear findings to share with the class.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><q>What is the position of point A relative to the origin?</q></li>
                <li><q>How do we write the position vector of A?</q></li>
                <li><q>What is the difference between a position vector and a regular vector?</q></li>
                <li><q>Can you think of real-world examples where we describe position relative to a starting point?</q></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_8uv0nuv3">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_ztgw2xh2">
            <p xml:id="auto_6342te8i">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_e15h65yg">
                <alert>What you require: </alert> Graph paper
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_q93wwlez">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bus2bj9u">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper as shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                            \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-6,-6) grid (6,6);

                            % Draw main grid (original)
                            \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-6,-6) grid (6,6);

                            % Draw axes
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (-5.5,0) -- (5.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (0,-5.5) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                            % Label x-axis
                            \foreach \x in {-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                                \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                            }

                            % Label y-axis
                            \foreach \y in {-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                                \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                            }
                            \node[below] at (-0.2,-0.2) {0};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_xzop360q">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_9sjq4vt5">
                    Plot the following points <m>A(1,1),B(3,5),C(2,1),D(4,-3) </m> on the graph.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_u4iuikun">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6yieuin8">
                    Draw a directed line from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dg0ef3m3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_20nnl4cy">
                    Draw another directed line from <m>D</m> to <m>C</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{CD}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_hpnog3dg">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_55bgesd8">
                     Determine the position vector of <m>B</m> relative to point <m>A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_s0tb0hwd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_f0ikg7mn">
                    Determine the position vector of <m>C</m> relative to point <m>D</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_llrp26kj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_w3efpqa9">
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_xgnxcb45">
        <p xml:id="auto_v1vjll1l">
            In <xref ref="illustration-position-vector-1"/> below, points <m>A(2,3)</m> and 
            <m>B(5,1)</m> are located in the plane relative to origin point O in the plane.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wu4xg6fb">
            The position vector of <m>A</m> is <m>\textbf{OA} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 - 0 \\ 3 - 0 \end{pmatrix} = \binom{2}{3}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_g2rzb4tg">
            The position vector of <m>B</m> is <m>\textbf{OB} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 - 0 \\ 1 - 0 \end{pmatrix} = \binom{5}{1}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_d63bxjht">
            Similarly, for point <m>A</m> in the plane its position vector <m>\textbf{OA}</m>
            is denoted by <m>\mathbf{a}</m>. Also for point <m>B</m> in the plane it's position vector 
            <m>\textbf{OB}</m> is denoted by <m>\mathbf{b}</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="illustration-position-vector-1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="45%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="examp-position-vector">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                    \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-3,-3) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw main grid (original)
                    \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-3,-3) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw axes
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                    % Label x-axis
                    \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                    }

                    % Label y-axis
                    \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4,5} {
                        \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                    }
                    \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {0};

                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (1.3,1.96) -- (1.31,1.98);
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (2.4,0.48) -- (2.45,0.49);

                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (2,3);
                    \coordinate (B) at (5,1);

                    % Draw vectors
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (A) node[midway, left] {\small $\mathbf{a}$};
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (B) node[midway, below] {\small $\mathbf{b}$};
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);

                    % Label points
                    \node[above left] at (A) {\small A(2,3)};
                    \node[right] at (B) {\small B(5,1)};
                    \node[above left] at (-0.1,-0.1) {\large O(0,0)};

                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalize the concept of position vectors.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vectors can start from any point. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Position vectors always start from the origin <m>O(0,0)</m>.</li>
                <li><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vector is the same as the point. <alert>Clarification:</alert> A point is a location; a position vector describes movement from the origin to that location.</li>
                <li><alert>Misconception:</alert> I need to perform a subtraction. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Since the origin is <m>(0,0)</m>, subtracting zero gives the point coordinates directly.</li>
                <li><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vectors are different from column vectors. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Position vectors are written using column vector notation.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Guide students through the worked example below, then assign independent practice.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Remind students that the position vector of <m>P(x,y)</m> is simply <m>\binom{x}{y}</m>.</li>
                <li>Have students read coordinates from the graph before writing the vector.</li>
                <li>Point out that position vectors in different quadrants will have negative components.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_k8qizai7">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_qn1zsef9">
                Find the position vector of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
            </p>
            <image width="80%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="example-position-vector">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                    \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-5,-5) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw main grid (original)
                    \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-5,-5) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw axes
                    \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                    \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                    % Label x-axis
                    \foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                    }

                    % Label y-axis
                    \foreach \y in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                        \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                    }
                    \node[below] at (-0.2,-0.1) {0};
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (3.4,-1.12) -- (3.5,-1.15);
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (1.9,-1.9) -- (2,-2);

                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (6,-2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (4,-4);

                    % Draw vectors
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (A) node[midway, above] {\small $\mathbf{a}$};
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (B) node[midway, below] {\small $\mathbf{b}$};
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);

                    % Label points
                    \node[right] at (A) {\small A};
                    \node[below] at (B) {\small B};
                    \node[above left] at (0,-0.1) {\small O(0,0)};

                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_pi6sj5nf">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hqlpgdv9">
                The position vector of A is <m>\textbf{OA } = \begin{pmatrix} 6 - 0 \\ -2 - 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 6  \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_13z5s7fu">
                Similarly the position vector of B is <m> \textbf{OB }= \begin{pmatrix} 4 - 0 \\ -4 - 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4  \\ -4 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Students complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scenario:</alert> A student is participating in a treasure hunt on the school sports field. They start at the centre of the field, which we call Point M. The student walks <m>30</m> metres directly North to a flag at Point N.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> Write the vector representing this movement using arrow notation.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> If this vector is assigned the letter <m>\mathbf{b}</m>, write it using tilde notation.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 3:</alert> If we set up a coordinate system with M at the origin and North as the positive <m>y</m> direction, what is the position vector of N?
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q1:</alert> <m>\overrightarrow{MN}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q2:</alert> <m>\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{b}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q3:</alert> <m>\overrightarrow{ON} = \binom{0}{30}</m> since the student moved <m>0</m> metres East/West and <m>30</m> metres North.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-position-vector">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_le0hpimn">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0d2scdwn">
                    Draw the following position vector on a graph paper:
                </p>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cmfkiuis">
                        <m>a = \left( \begin{matrix} 10 \\ -2 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_c8c29wod">
                        <m>b = \left( \begin{matrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6sg3cib0">
                        <m>c = \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 8 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_7jyo5lfb">
                        <m>d = \left( \begin{matrix} -11 \\ 6 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_bnts7u9a">
                        <m>e = \left( \begin{matrix} 4 \\ 4 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_jogzn4rr">
                        <m>f = \left( \begin{matrix} -1 \\ 12 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_goiyf9q8">
                        <m>g = \left( \begin{matrix} 5 \\ 3 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_xvpsf1im">
                        <m>h = \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ 13 \end{matrix}\right)</m>
                    </p>
                    
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_xdvj1z3p">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_5s9wtlig">
                    Use <xref ref="example-pos-vect1"/> below to write the position vectors 
                    of points <m>M,E,D,A</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="example-pos-vect1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image label="example-pos1-vector">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                            % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                            \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-5,-7) grid (7,8);

                            % Draw main grid (original)
                            \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-5,-7) grid (7,8);

                            % Draw axes
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (-4.5,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (0,-6) -- (0,7.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                            % Label x-axis
                            \foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                                \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                            }

                            % Label y-axis
                            \foreach \y in {-6,-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
                                \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                            }
                            \node[below] at (-0.2,-0.2) {0};

                            % Define points
                            \coordinate (A) at (1,1);
                            \coordinate (B) at (3,4);

                            \coordinate (E) at (-3,1);
                            \coordinate (F) at (-3,4);

                            \coordinate (C) at (1,-3);
                            \coordinate (D) at (3,-6);

                            \coordinate (M) at (-4,-4);
                            \coordinate (N) at (-2,-2);

                            % Draw vectors
                            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
                            \draw[thick] (E) -- (F);
                            \draw[thick] (C) -- (D);
                            \draw[thick] (M) -- (N);

                            % Label points
                            \node[left] at (A) {\large A};
                            \node[above right] at (B) {\large B};

                            \node[above] at (C) {\large C};
                            \node[below] at (D) {\large D};

                            \node[below] at (E) {\large E};
                            \node[above] at (F) {\large F};

                            \node[left] at (M) {\large M};
                            \node[right] at (N) {\large N};

                             % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                             \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (A) -- (2,2.5);
                             \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (E) -- (-3,2.5);
                             \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (D) -- (2,-4.5);
                             \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (M) -- (-3,-3);

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Provide pre-drawn coordinate planes with the origin clearly marked.</li>
                <li>Use colour coding: one colour for the origin, another for the point.</li>
                <li>Start with points in the first quadrant (positive <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>) to simplify.</li>
                <li>Provide step-by-step templates for finding position vectors.</li>
                <li>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Encourage students to create their own position vector problems.</li>
                <li>Ask students to explain why position vectors always start from the origin.</li>
                <li>Provide mixed practice with points in all four quadrants.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Explore the relationship between position vectors and displacement vectors.</li>
                <li>Investigate: if we know the position vectors of two points, how can we find the vector between them?</li>
                <li>Challenge: Given position vectors <m>\mathbf{a} = \binom{3}{4}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \binom{1}{2}</m>, find the vector from A to B.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity — GPS Treasure Hunt:</alert> In pairs, students set up a coordinate system, choose 5 treasure locations, write the position vector for each, calculate the distance from the origin using the Pythagorean theorem, and create a map showing all locations with their position vectors.
        </p>
    </axiom>


